,"1256":"1256","1560":"1560","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Inglaterra":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1270–":"1270–Overleden","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1270–Female":"1270–Overleden","1290–1560":"1290–1560","1256–Male":"1256–Overleden","1250–Female":"1250–Overleden","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1560":"1560","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Inglaterra":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1270–":"1270–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1290–1560":"1290–1560","1256–Male":"1256–Deceased","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1560":"1560","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Inglaterra":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whitton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Whitton in Morebattle (Roxburghshire). The placename is from Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’, as with many of the places in 2 below.","English: habitational name from any of the places called Whitton (Durham, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Northumberland, Shropshire, Suffolk) or Witton (Cheshire, Durham, Lancashire, Herefordshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, North Yorkshire); or possibly from Wyton (Huntingdonshire, East Yorkshire); or possibly from Weeton, Market Weighton, or Little Weighton (East Yorkshire). The placenames do not all share the same etymology but most of their post-medieval spellings are interchangeable. Most of the placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> or Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some, for example Witton in Warwickshire, derive from Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farmstead’ + <i>tūn</i>, and some others, for example Witton in Norfolk, derive from Old English <i>widu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>tūn</i>. Whitton in Lincolnshire derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> (genitive <i>Hwītan</i>) or Old English <i>hwīt</i> (dative <i>hwītan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. Witton in Lancashire derives from the Old English personal <i>Witta</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","English: in Devon, this surname is a variant of   Whiddon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitten","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitton   or   Whiting  ."]},{"name":"Whetten","meanings":["English, Scottish, or northern Irish: variant of   Whitton  ."]},{"name":"Whiddon","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from any of numerous minor places in Devon named Whiddon. Some are named with Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ or <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’; others with Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>dūn</i> or <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]},{"name":"Whiton","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Whitton  . This surname is now rare in Britain.","History: James Whiton of Hingham, Norfolk, England, came to Plymouth, MA, in 1635."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon Whitton was born in 1270, in England, his father, Thomas De WHITTON, was 14 and his mother, mis whitton, was 20. He had at least 1 son with mis whitton."},"et":{"1270–":"1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1290–1560":"1290–1560","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1560":"1560","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Inglaterra":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1270–":"1270–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1290–1560":"1290–1560","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1560":"1560","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Inglaterra":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1270–":"1270–Décédé","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1270–Female":"1270–Décé